Scalability : 
  It is an ability of a system to handle increased load by adding resources			How to measure the scalability : 
  - requests per second : number of API calls the system handles
  - concurrent users : more number of users actively using the system
  - Data transfer per unit 
  - Query rate : DB queries per second 
  - message rate : number of messages processed per unit(ex: 10000 mgs/s)
  - performance load testing 

Types of scaling : 
  - Vertical Scaling :  Adding more power to the existing system to handle the load
    (Ex: A has 4 CPU’s and 16 GB ram => A Now has 32 CPU’s and 256 GB ram)
  Pros : 
    1: No code changes required , just upgrade to higher version
    2: low latency : due to high performance , cause low delay between user request and server response (Low latency means the system responds very quickly after a user sends a        request.)

When to use Vertical Scaling: 
  - Databases with data in one place – All data stays on one server, so it’s faster and easier to manage.
  - Applications needing strong consistency – One server helps keep data accurate and avoids conflicts.
  - Predictable, moderate growth – If traffic grows slowly, you can just upgrade the server hardware. 🚀
  - Early-stage startups – Easier and simpler to manage one powerful server than many servers.

Pros (Advantages)
  - Simple to use – No need to change the application code. Just upgrade to a more powerful machine.
  - Lower latency – All data is on the same server, so responses are faster.
  - Less complexity – Only one server, so there are no network or data synchronization problems.

Cons (Disadvantages)
  - Hardware limits – You cannot grow beyond the biggest machine available.
  - Single point of failure – If the server crashes, the whole system stops working.
  - Expensive at large scale – Bigger machines cost much more than smaller ones.
  - Downtime during upgrades – Moving to a bigger server may require stopping the system for some time.

